  tutorialCodeLine1: int x = 4; int y = 3;
  tutorialCodeLine2: if (x + y > 6) cout << x * y;
  tutorialCodeLine3: else cout << x - y;
  tutorialCodeLine4: 
  tutorialExplanationLine1: int x = 4; int y = 3; -> Variables x and y store 4 and
    3.
  tutorialExplanationLine2: if (x + y > 6) cout << x * y; -> 4 + 3 = 7, so condition
    is true.
  tutorialExplanationLine3: else cout << x - y; -> Else branch is not used here.
  tutorialExplanationLine4: 
  tutorialCalculationLine: "4 + 3 = 7 > 6, so 4 \xD7 3 = 12"
  tutorialFinalLine: So the correct answer is 12.
